integration of inDrop and 10x data

Overview

This is a final massaging script well load the data, get it into one big dataframe, mark the metadata with which experiment it is from, which sample it is from, etc so we have all of the information we need in one place to do the downstream analysis.

drop genes missing from inDrop data

indrop = readRDS(file.path("data", "indrop", "counts.rds"))
tenx = readRDS(file.path("data", "10x", "counts.rds"))
indrop_md = readRDS(file.path("data", "indrop", "metadata.rds"))
tenx_md = readRDS(file.path("data", "10x", "metadata.rds"))
md = readr::read_csv(file.path("..", "metadata", "sample_metadata.csv"))

We can see despite feeding in the same annotations, we end up with about 500 more genes annotated in the 10x data than in the inDrop data. The reason for this is that rapmap when creating the index will dump transcripts that are identical to each other, and just retain one. CellRanger retains them all. Here we will subset down the 10x data to exclude the 500 genes which were removed from the inDrop data. This sounds like a lot, but there are only two genes which have non-zero counts in the 10x dataset, so we are really only excluding two genes. And the two genes which have counts only have two and one count total between them, so we are not missing anything by excluding these genes.

excluded = tenx[!rownames(tenx) %in% rownames(indrop),]
excluded_stats = data.frame(gene=rownames(excluded),
                            present=rowSums(excluded > 0) > 0)
knitr::kable(excluded_stats %>%
  group_by(present) %>%
  summarise(count=n()))
present count
FALSE 543 
nonzero = excluded_stats %>%
  dplyr::filter(present) %>%
  pull(gene)

knitr::kable(data.frame(total_counts=rowSums(excluded[nonzero,])))
total_counts 
tenx = tenx[rownames(indrop),]

add sample metadata

Now we will expand the 10x metadata, to include information about which sample it was from, the technology that was used and the technical replicate. Well do the same for the inDrop data. Were doing this separately because the cells are named differently.

tenx_md = tenx_md %>%
  tidyr::separate(cell, into=c("drop1", "library", "drop2"), remove=FALSE) %>%
  dplyr::select(-c("drop1", "drop2")) %>%
  left_join(md, by="library") %>%
  dplyr::select(-c("barcode", "rc_barcode", "passed_cellranger_filter"))

We do the same for the inDrop metadata, linking up the sample-level metadata with the barcodes identified in the data.

indrop_md = indrop_md %>%
  tidyr::separate(cell, into=c("drop1", "drop2"), sep=":", remove=FALSE) %>%
  tidyr::separate(drop1, into=c("drop3", "rc_barcode"), sep="-") %>%
  left_join(md, by="rc_barcode") %>%
  dplyr::select(-c("barcode", "rc_barcode", "drop2", "drop3"))

combine inDrop and 10x data

Now we can combine the two datasets along with their metadata together into one big experiment, which we can use going forward. We make sure the metadata and the count data are in the same order and the output the counts and metadata tables for future use.

dat = cbind(tenx, indrop)
md = rbind(tenx_md, indrop_md)
rownames(md) = md$cell
dat = dat[, rownames(md)]

We can see that most of the cells are contained in two samples, the 10x_2 and the inDrop_2 sample. In particular they are driven by the G4 library for the 10x and and the gut4 library for the inDrop data.

Below is the nUMI vs nGene plot, colored by mitochondrial content, broken out by the four samples. This looks like what we expected, so I think we are good to go.

ggplot(md, aes(nUMI, nGenes, color=pctMito)) +
  facet_wrap(~sample) +
  geom_point()  +
  scale_x_log10(
    breaks = scales::trans_breaks("log10", function(x) 10^x),
    labels = scales::trans_format("log10", scales::math_format(10^.x))) +
  scale_y_log10(
    breaks = scales::trans_breaks("log10", function(x) 10^x),
    labels = scales::trans_format("log10", scales::math_format(10^.x))) +
  annotation_logticks(sides='bl') +
  scale_color_viridis()
